@node Info "Information"


			  IMAGEFX AREXX COMMANDS
				RELEASE 2.0


   This document assumes that you are familiar with programming in the
Arexx language, and only describes the commands specific to ImageFX.

   All commands, unless otherwise noted, return a non-zero error code if
something went wrong. This includes cancelling the operation.  If the
return code is 0, then a result string may be provided.

   Those commands marked with (Arexx Only) may only be used properly from
an Arexx macro.  All other commands may be used in scripts, key
definitions, toolbox definitions, the command shell, or Arexx macros at
will.

   When a command is invoked from the shell, any result string returned
will be printed to the console.  Arexx errors will also be displayed on the
console.

   Commands and arguments marked with (2.0) are new for ImageFX 2.0.

HOW TO READ THIS DOCUMENT

   FORMAT
      This gives the command name followed by its argument template.  The
      argument template follows the standard AmigaDOS CLI command format.
      Each keyword (separated by commas) represents a possible argument.
      Here are the types of arguments:

	   /A	Always required (cumulative with other modifiers).
	   /F	Final argument (rest of line).
	   /K	Keyword required.
	   /N	Number argument.
	   /S	Switch keyword.

      Example:

      FORMAT
	   RequestFile Title/A,Path,File,Pattern

      There are four possible arguments to this command.  The first one
      MUST be specified.  The remaining three are optional.  All are text
      arguments.  This template can be filled in any of the following ways:

      /* the complete longhand format: */
      RequestFile TITLE "Load Image" PATH "DH0:" FILE "Image" PATTERN
      "#?.pic"

      /* the abbreviated format (if the keywords are not specified, the
      arguments are filled in in order.) */
      RequestFile "Load Image" "DH0:" "Image" "#?.pic"

      /* only the first argument is required: */
      RequestFile "Load Image"

      /* to skip arguments... you MUST use the "pattern" keyword in this
      case otherwise the "#?.pic" will go into the "path" argument: */
      RequestFile "Load Image" PATTERN "#?.pic"

      /* quotation marks around arguments are only necessary if there are
      spaces in the argument. */

   FUNCTION
      Describes what this command actually does.

   INPUTS
      Describes in detail all of the possible arguments to the command.

   RESULT
      Describes the result string returned from the command, if one is in
      fact returned.  If the command is used from Arexx, this result string
      will be found in the RESULT variable.  If the command is typed in the
      command shell, then the result string is just printed out to the
      console.	The result string is lost when invoked from a key, script,
      or the toolbox.

      All commands will return a result code in the Arexx variable RC
      regardless of whether they return a result string or not.  A result
      code of zero indicates success.

   SEE ALSO
      Possible related commands.
@endnode


@node ActiveColor "ActiveColor"

ACTIVECOLOR

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      ActiveColor Register/N,Next/S,Prev/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Select the "active" color register in the palette.  The active color
      is used for all drawing functions.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Register@{uu}
	 Specific color register to activate.  Should be in the range of 0
	 - 255.

      @{u}Next@{uu}
	 Activate the next higher color register.

      @{u}Prev@{uu}
	 Activate the next lower (previous) color register.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the previous active color register, before the change.

   @{b}EXAMPLES@{ub}
      /* activate fourth color register: */
	 ActiveColor 4
	 /* jump to next higher color register: */
	 ActiveColor NEXT

@endnode

@node ActiveLayer "ActiveLayer"

ACTIVELAYER (3.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      ActiveLayer LayerNum/N,Top/S,Next/S,Prev/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Set the active or selected layer in the current image.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}LayerNum@{uu}
	 Layer number to activate.  The background layer is always
	 layer 0, with higher layers proceeding up from 0.

      @{u}Top@{uu}
	 Activate the topmost layer.

      @{u}Next@{uu}
	 Activate the next higher layer.

      @{u}Prev@{uu}
	 Activate the previous (next lower) layer.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the previous active layer number, before the change.

@endnode

@node ActiveRange "ActiveRange"

ACTIVERANGE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      ActiveRange Range/N,Next/S,Prev/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Set the active palette range.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Range@{uu}
	 Palette range to make active directly (0-8).  Range 0 is taken to
	 mean the ALL range.

      @{u}Next@{uu}
	 Cycle up through the ranges.

      @{u}Prev@{uu}
	 Cycle down through the ranges.

      Note: If no arguments are given, no change is made.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the current active range number, before any changes are made.

   @{b}EXAMPLES@{ub}
      /* activate the "all" range */
	 ActiveRange 0
	 /* activate color range 4 */
	 ActiveRange 4

@endnode

@node Add "Add"

ADD (OBSOLETE)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Add Alpha/S,Scale/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform a composite add operation to the main and swap buffers.  For
      backwards compatibility, this command uses the old-style Add routine.
      See the Composite hook for details on the new-style compositing
      functions.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Alpha@{uu}
	 If specified, the alpha channel will be used as a blend control
	 image during the composite.

      @{u}Scale@{uu}
	 If specified, the swap buffer will be scaled to fit the region
	 processed.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}EXAMPLES@{ub}
      /* composite add the main and swap buffers */
	 Add
	 /* composite add, using alpha channel */
	 Add ALPHA
	 /* composite add, scaling swap into region */
	 Add SCALE

@endnode

@node AddArea "AddArea"

ADDAREA

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      AddArea X/N/A,Y/N/A

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Add a point to the current area definition.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}X,Y@{uu}
	 Coordinates of the new point, in buffer pixels.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}EXAMPLES@{ub}
      /* add point 100,50 to current area */
	 AddArea 100 50

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      NewArea,Poly,FilledPoly,Airbrush,FreeDraw,
	 FreeLine,FilledFree,PolyRegion

@endnode

@node Airbrush "Airbrush"

AIRBRUSH

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Airbrush

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Draw into the main buffer using the airbrush.  The path the airbrush
      follows is defined by calls to NewArea/AddArea.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}EXAMPLES@{ub}
      Airbrush

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      NewArea,AddArea

@endnode

@node AirbrushSettings "AirbrushSettings"

AIRBRUSHSETTINGS

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      AirbrushSettings
	 Radius/N,Nozzle/N,Spray/S,Smudge/S,Paint/S,Realtime/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Define the airbrush state.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Radius@{uu}
	 Radius of the airbrush, in pixels (1-255).

      @{u}Nozzle@{uu}
	 Nozzle size of the airbrush (1-100).

      @{u}Spray,Smudge,Paint@{uu}
	 Airbrush operation mode.

      @{u}Realtime@{uu}
	 Enable realtime airbrush.  (2.0)

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the state of the airbrush before any changes are made, in the
      form "radius nozzle mode [REALTIME]".

   @{b}EXAMPLES@{ub}
      /* radius=10, nozzle=50, smudge */
	 AirbrushSettings 10 50 SMUDGE

@endnode

@node AllowPainting "AllowPainting"

ALLOWPAINTING (2.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      AllowPainting On/S,Off/S,Toggle/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Set the state of the "Allow Painting" flag in the region window.
      When enabled, you can use the painting tools and draw while a region
      is defined.  The drawing will be constrained to the region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}On@{uu}
	 Allow painting with regions.

      @{u}Off@{uu}
	 Do not allow painting - drawing will affect the region mask.

      @{u}Toggle@{uu}
	 Toggle the state of the flag.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the previous state of the flag in RESULT.

@endnode

@node Alpha2Buffer "Alpha2Buffer"

ALPHA2BUFFER

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Alpha2Buffer Name,Force/S,New/S,Move/S
      CopyFromAlpha Name,Force/S,New/S,Move/S
      AlphaToBuffer Name,Force/S,New/S,Move/S  (1.50)

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Copy the contents of the alpha channel into the main image buffer,
      destroying the previous contents.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Name@{uu}  (3.2)
	 When copying into a new buffer, this sets the name for the
	 new buffer.  Only used when you also specify the New option
	 below.

      @{u}Force@{uu}
	 Bypass the normal "Are you sure?" requester.

      @{u}New@{uu}  (3.2)
	 Copies the alpha channel image data to a brand new buffer.
	 The new buffer name is the same is the current image's with
	 the word "Alpha" appended to it.

      @{u}Move@{uu}  (3.2)
	 Deletes the alpha channel plane after the copy is complete.
	 Generally only useful when you also specify the New option.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}EXAMPLES@{ub}
      /* copy alpha to main, disable "okay" req */
	 Alpha2Buffer FORCE

@endnode

@node AlphaChannel "AlphaChannel"

ALPHACHANNEL

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      AlphaChannel Off/S,Frisket/S,Texture/S,Toggle/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Select the role of the alpha channel during drawing operations.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Off@{uu}
	 Alpha channel is not used at all.

      @{u}Frisket@{uu}
	 Alpha channel is used as a frisket.

      @{u}Texture@{uu}
	 Alpha channel is used to texturize the drawing.

      @{u}Toggle@{uu}
	 The state is toggled between either Frisket or Texture.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the state of the alpha channel before any change is made,
      either "Off", "Frisket", or "Texture".

@endnode

@node AntiAlias "AntiAlias"

ANTIALIAS (OBSOLETE)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      AntiAlias Threshold/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform an anti-aliasing effect on the current image or region.  For
      backwards compatibility, this command uses the old-style (1.5) anti-
      alias routine.  See the AntiAlias hook for details on the new anti-
      alias routine.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Threshold@{uu}
	 Threshold to control how heavy the anti-aliasing is (0-255).

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node AspectLock "AspectLock"

ASPECTLOCK (3.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      AspectLock On/S,Off/S,Toggle/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Change the aspect lock setting for the current preview window.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}On, Off@{uu}
	 Set the aspect lock on or off.

      @{u}Toggle@{uu}
	 Toggle the aspect lock setting.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Bar "Bar"

BAR

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Bar Iteration/N/A

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Advance the status bar to show the completion of the given number of
      iterations.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Iteration@{uu}
	 Number of iterations completed.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      BeginBar,EndBar

@endnode

@node BeginBar "BeginBar"

BEGINBAR

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      BeginBar Title/A,Max/N/A

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Start a status bar operation.  Locks out user input to the menus,
      initializes the status bar area, and displays a "busy" pointer.

      You should ALWAYS remember to follow any calls to BeginBar with an
      eventual call to EndBar.	The user will not be able to click on any
      gadgets until you do.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Title@{uu}
	 Title to put in the status area, should be short enough to fit
	 (around 10 characters or so).

      @{u}Max@{uu}
	 Total number of iterations expected in the operation.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      EndBar,Bar

@endnode

@node Bezier "Bezier"

BEZIER

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Bezier X1/N,Y1/N,X2/N,Y2/N,X3/N,Y3/N,X4/N,Y4/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Draw a bezier curve in the main buffer, using the supplied
      coordinates to define the curve.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}X1,Y1@{uu}
	 Starting point of the curve.

      @{u}X2,Y2@{uu}
	 Ending point of the curve.

      @{u}X3,Y3@{uu}
	 Control point #1.

      @{u}X4,Y4@{uu}
	 Control point #2.

      Note:  A three-point curve may be simulated by making X3,Y3 and
	 X4,Y4 the same spot.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Blend "Blend"

BLEND

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Blend Percent/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Change and/or retrieve the current blending percentage.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Percent@{uu}
	 New blend percentage, in the range of 1 - 100.  If not specified,
	 no change is made.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Old blend percentage, before the change.

@endnode

@node Blue "Blue"

BLUE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Blue Adjust/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Adjust the blue content of the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Adjust@{uu}
	 Amount to adjust the blue (-127 to +127).  This number is added
	 directly to each blue value.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Blur "Blur"

BLUR

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Blur Amount/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform a blur effect on the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Amount@{uu}
	 Intensity of the blur effect, should be 1 - 16.  If not given, a
	 requester will be presented.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Box "Box"

BOX

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Box Left/N,Top/N,Width/N,Height/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Draw a box into the current buffer at the given location, using the
      current pen or brush, and all of the current drawing settings.  If
      Scissors or MagicScissors has been turned on, this will cut the area
      defined by the box out as a brush.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Left,Top@{uu}
	 Upper left corner of the box, in pixels.

      @{u}Width,Height@{uu}
	 Width and height of the box, in pixels.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node BoxRegion "BoxRegion"

BOXREGION

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      BoxRegion Add/S,Subtract/S,X1/N,Y1/N,X2/N,Y2/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Define a rectangular region in the main buffer.  Subsequent image
      processing operations will be constrained to this region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Add@{uu}
	 If specified, this region is to be merged in with the existing
	 region.  Otherwise the new region supercedes any existing regions.

      @{u}Subtract (2.0)@{uu}
	 If specified, this region will be subtracted from the existing
	 region.

      @{u}X1,Y1@{uu}
	 Upper left corner of the region, in buffer pixels.

      @{u}X2,Y2@{uu}
	 Lower right corner of the region, in buffer pixels.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Brightness "Brightness"

BRIGHTNESS

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Brightness Adjust/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Adjust the brightness of the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Adjust@{uu}
	 Amount to adjust the brightness (-127 to +127).

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node BrushHandle "BrushHandle"

BRUSHHANDLE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      BrushHandle XOffset/N,YOffset/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Modify the position of the current brush's handle.  The handle is the
      position where the mouse pointer appears over the brush, by default
      it is the middle of the brush.  You can modify the position with this
      command.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}XOffset@{uu}
	 X coordinate of the new brush handle, in pixels.

      @{u}YOffset@{uu}
	 Y coordinate of the new brush handle, in pixels.

      Note:  If no arguments are given, the program will allow you to
	 interactively adjust the brush handle.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Brush2Swap "Brush2Swap"

BRUSH2SWAP

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Brush2Swap
      BrushToSwap (1.50)

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Copy the current brush into the swap buffer, destroying whatever was
      there previously.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node BrushToBack "BrushToBack"

BRUSH2BACK (2.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      BrushToBack
      Brush2Back

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Push the current brush into the "background", to make room for
      another one.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      SelectBrush,NextBrush,PrevBrush

@endnode

@node Buffer2Alpha "Buffer2Alpha"

BUFFER2ALPHA

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Buffer2Alpha Source,Move/S
      CopyToAlpha Source,Move/S
      BufferToAlpha Source,Move/S (1.50)

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Copy the contents of the main image buffer into the alpha channel.
      Color image data is converted to greyscale using a simple conversion.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Source@{uu}  (3.2)
	 Optional name of buffer from which to copy image data.  If not
	 specified, image data is copied from the current main buffer.
	 Using this option, you can copy image data from any arbitrary
	 buffer into the current buffer's alpha channel.

      @{u}Move@{uu}  (3.2)
	 When copying from a different source buffer, adding this argument
	 will delete the source buffer after the copy is complete.  Has no
	 effect when copying from the main buffer into it's own alpha
	 channel.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Buffer2Swap "Buffer2Swap"

BUFFER2SWAP

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Buffer2Swap
      BufferToSwap (1.50)
      CopyToSwap (1.50)
      Copy2Swap (1.50)

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Copy the main image buffer into the swap buffer, destroying whatever
      may have been in the swap buffer.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node BufferToBack "BufferToBack"

BUFFER2BACK (2.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      BufferToBack
      Buffer2Back

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Pushes the main buffer into the "background".  This puts the buffer
      into the multiple buffer list and allows a new buffer to be loaded
      while keeping the old one.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      SelectBuffer,NextBuffer,PrevBuffer

@endnode

@node Channel "Channel"

CHANNEL

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Channel ChanSpec

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Define the channel mask for subsequent image processing and drawing
      operations.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}ChanSpec@{uu}
	 A string indicating which channels are to be active.  The string
	 consists of the letters “R”, “G”, and “B” in varying combinations.
	 For example, a channel spec of “RG” would turn on the Red and
	 Green channels, while turning off the Blue channel.  “B” would
	 turn on only the Blue channel.  “RGB” enables all channels (the
	 normal default).

      Note:  If no arguments are given, no change is made.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the channel state before any changes are made.

@endnode

@node ClearBuffer "ClearBuffer"

CLEARBUFFER

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      ClearBuffer Force/S,Red/N,Green/N,Blue/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Clear the current image buffer to a certain color, usually black.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Force@{uu}
	 If specified, the normal "Are you sure?" requester will be
	 bypassed.

      @{u}Red@{uu}
	 Red value (0 - 255) of new buffer color.

      @{u}Green@{uu}
	 Green value (0 - 255) of new buffer color.

      @{u}Blue@{uu}
	 Blue value (0 - 255) of new buffer color.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node CmdShell "CmdShell"

CMDSHELL

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      CmdShell Console

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Enters the ImageFX command shell window.	Within this window, you can
      enter commands directly for ImageFX to execute.  This is a handy way
      to experiment with the ImageFX command language.	To exit the command
      shell, press RETURN on a blank line by itself.

      The command shell detaches from the program, so you can leave it open
      and continue to use program features.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Console@{uu}
	 A standard console specification used for the command shell
	 window.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Color2Cmap "Color2CMAP"

COLOR2CMAP (3.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Color2CMAP Colors/N,Dither/N,Direction/N,Threshold/N
      ColorToCMAP Colors/N,Dither/N,Direction/N,Threshold/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Convert the current RGB image buffer into a colormapped image, using
      the current Quantize module for color reduction.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Colors@{uu}
	 Number of colors in the resultant image.

      @{u}Dither, Direction, Limit@{uu}
	 Specify dither settings.  If not specified, the default of
	 Floyd Zig-Zag dithering will be used.

	 Dither:  0=None, 1=Floyd, 2=FloydR, 3=EDD, 4=Order.

	 Direction:  0=LtoR, 1=RtoL, 2=ZigZag.

	 Limit:  0=None, 1=Low, 2=Medium, 3=High.

      Note:  If no arguments are given, a window will be presented
	 asking for conversion settings.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Color2Grey "Color2Grey"

COLOR2GREY

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Color2Grey RWgt/N,GWgt/N,BWgt/N,Luma/S,Grey/S
      Color2Gray RWgt/N,GWgt/N,BWgt/N,Luma/S,Grey/S  (1.50)
      ColorToGrey RWgt/N,GWgt/N,BWgt/N,Luma/S,Grey/S  (1.50)
      ColorToGray RWgt/N,GWgt/N,BWgt/N,Luma/S,Grey/S  (1.50)

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Convert a 24-bit color image to 8-bit greyscale, using a specified
      weighting.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}RWgt,GWgt,BWgt@{uu}
	 The “weights” to assign to each of the red, green, and blue
	 components respectively.  Each weight is expressed as a
	 percentage, where 1000 represents 100%.  The total of the weights
	 should normally add to 100%, but certain interesting effects can
	 be acheived with non-unity weight dispersions.

      @{u}Luma@{uu}
	 Uses a preset "lumascale" weight distribution (R=299,G=587,B=114).

      @{u}Grey@{uu}
	 Uses a preset "average" weight distribution (R=333,G=334,B=333).

      Note:  If no arguments are given, the standard Color To Grey
	 window is presented.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node ColorLimit "ColorLimit"

COLORLIMIT

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      ColorLimit RLo/N,RHi/N,GLo/N,GHi/N,BLo/N,BHi/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform a color limiting effect on the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}RLo,RHi@{uu}
	 Lower and upper clipping points of red channel.

      @{u}GLo,GHi@{uu}
	 Lower and upper clipping points of green channel.

      @{u}BLo,BHi@{uu}
	 Lower and upper clipping points of blue channel.

      Note:  For greyscale images, only the red channel is used.

      Note:  If no arguments are given, the standard Color Limit
	 window is presented.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node ColorSpace "ColorSpace"

COLORSPACE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      ColorSpace RGB/S,HSV/S,CMY/S,YIQ/S,YUV/S,Next/S,Prev/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Set the colorspace used by the palette display, updating the palette
      sliders and such if appropriate.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}RGB,HSV,CMY,YIQ,YUV@{uu}
	 Color space to set the palette to directly.

      @{u}Next@{uu}
	 Cycle up through the color space choices.

      @{u}Prev@{uu}
	 Cycle down through the color space choices.

      Note:  If no arguments are given, no change is made.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the name of the current colorspace, before any changes.

@endnode

@node ColorTransform "ColorTransform"

COLORTRANSFORM

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      ColorTransform File

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform a user color transformation on the current image or region,
      using the table found in the given file.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}File@{uu}
	 Name of a transformation file.  If not given, the standard Color
	 Transform editor will be presented.  If a full path is not given,
	 the file is assumed to reside in the current Transform path (as
	 set in prefs).

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node ComplexRequest "ComplexRequest"

COMPLEXREQUEST

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      ComplexRequest Title/A,NumGads/N/A,Stem/A,Width/N,Height/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Build a complex requester to present to the user, consisting of a
      number of types of gadgets.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Title@{uu}
	 Title of the requester, to appear at its top.

      @{u}NumGads@{uu}
	 Number of gadgets defined for the requester, not including "Okay"
	 and "Cancel", which are always present.

      @{u}Stem@{uu}
	 Stem variable where the gadgets are defined.  Each element in the
	 stem array contains an encoded string defining a type of gadget.
	 The array starts at Stem.1 and goes through Stem.N.  The strings
	 are generally encoded as follows:

		    Type/LeftEdge/TopEdge[/Argument(s)]

	 Some gadget types may have more than one argument; each argument
	 is separated by a slash (/).

	 Here is a list of all the gadget types available:

     B@{u}/x/y/Label/ReturnCode (2.0)@{uu}
	 Button gadget.  The X,Y coordinates define the upper left corner
	 of the gadget.  Label is the text to put inside of the button.
	 ReturnCode is the value returned to Arexx if this button is
	 pressed (defaults to 1000) - you should use values higher than
	 1000 to avoid confusion with regular error codes.

     F@{u}/x/y/Label/Title/Path/Pattern/File (1.50)@{uu}
	 File Request button.  The X,Y coordinates define the upper left
	 corner of the gadget.	Label is the text to put inside of the
	 button.  Title is the title for the file requester that appears
	 after hitting the button, Path is the initial path for the file
	 requester, Pattern is the initial file pattern for the file
	 requester, and File is the initial file.

     G@{u}/x/y/Label/Title/Path/Pattern/File (2.0)@{uu}
	 File Request image button.  The X,Y coordinates define the upper
	 left corner of the gadget.  Label is the text to put inside of the
	 button.  Title is the title for the file requester that appears
	 after hitting the button, Path is the initial path for the file
	 requester, Pattern is the initial file pattern for the file
	 requester, and File is the initial file.  Same as “F” but uses a
	 disk image in the button.

     I@{u}/x/y/Label/Default@{uu}
	 Integer string gadget.  The X,Y coordinates define the upper left
	 corner of the gadget.	Label is the text to appear to the left of
	 the gadget.  Default indicates the initial contents of the gadget.

     J@{u}/x/y/w/Label/Default (1.50)@{uu}
	 Variable-width Integer string gadget.	The X,Y coordinates define
	 the upper left corner of the gadget.  W is the width of the
	 integer gadget in pixels.  Label is the text to appear to the left
	 of the gadget.  Default indicates the initial contents of the
	 gadget.

     S@{u}/x/y/Label/Default@{uu}
	 String gadget.  The X,Y coordinates define the upper left corner
	 of the gadget.  Label is the text to appear to the left of the
	 gadget.  Default indicates the initial contents of the gadget.

     T@{u}/x/y/w/Just/Label/Default (1.50)@{uu}
	 Varible-width String gadget.  The X,Y coordinates define the upper
	 left corner of the gadget.  W is the width of the string gadget in
	 pixels.  Just is the justification of the text within the gadget;
	 0 = left justified, 1 = right justified, 2 = center justified.
	 Label is the text to appear to the left of the gadget.  Default
	 indicates the initial contents of the gadget.

     X@{u}/x/y/Label/Default@{uu}
	 Checkbox gadget.  The X,Y coordinates define the upper left corner
	 of the gadget.  Label is the text that is to appear to the right
	 side of the gadget.  Default indicates the initial state of the
	 checkbox (0 or 1).

     C@{u}/x/y/Label/Count/Choice1/Choice2/.../ChoiceN@{uu}
	 Cycler gadget.  The X,Y coordinates define the upper left corner
	 of the gadget.  Label is the text to appear to the left of the
	 gadget.  Count indicates how many choices there are in this cycle
	 gadget.  Following the count is the actual text of the choices,
	 each separated by a slash (/).  There must be the indicated number
	 of choice labels.

     D@{u}/x/y/w/Label/Count/Choice1/Choice2/.../ChoiceN/Initial (2.0)@{uu}
	 Variable-width Cycler gadget.	The X,Y coordinates define the
	 upper left corner of the gadget. W is the width of the string
	 gadget in pixels.  Label is the text to appear to the left of the
	 gadget.  Count indicates how many choices there are in this cycle
	 gadget.  Following the count is the actual text of the choices,
	 each separated by a slash (/).  There must be the indicated number
	 of choice labels.  Initial is the initially selected choice.

     L@{u}/x/y/pen/just/Label (1.50)@{uu}
	 Label "gadget".  Defines a text element to be placed in the
	 complex requester, not an actual gadget.  The X,Y coordinates
	 normally define the upper left corner of the text.  Pen is the pen
	 number to use in rendering the text (in the default ImageFX
	 palette, 0=grey, 1=black, 2=white, 3=blue).  Just is the
	 justification to use in rendering the text; 0 = left justify, 1 =
	 right justify (ie. the X coordinate is really the right edge of
	 the text), and 2 = center justify (ie. the X coordinate is really
	 the center of the text).  Label is the text to render.

      @{u}Width,Height@{uu}
	 Optional width and height of the requester.  Defaults to 400 width
	 and 65 height.

      Note:  In ImageFX 2.0, a new recessed border is placed around
	 the Complex requester, which may affect your gadget
	 placement slightly.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the user's selection for each gadget in a stem variable
      called RESULT.  Thus, RESULT.1 is the user's choice for the first
      gadget, RESULT.2 is the choice for the second gadget, etc.

@endnode

@node Contrast "Contrast"

CONTRAST

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Contrast Adjust/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Adjust the contrast of the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Adjust@{uu}
	 Amount to adjust the contrast (-127 to +127).

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Convolve "Convolve"

CONVOLVE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Convolve File

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform a user convolution effect on the current image or region,
      using a specified matrix file.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}File@{uu}
	 Filename containing the convolution matrix definition.  If not
	 given, then the standard User Convolve editor window will be
	 presented.  If a full path is not given, the file is assumed to
	 reside in the current Convolve path.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node CopyColor "CopyColor"

COPYCOLOR

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      CopyColor From/N,To/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Copy one color region over another in the palette.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}From@{uu}
	 Source color register (0-255).

      @{u}To@{uu}
	 Destination color register (0-255).

      Note:  If no arguments are given, the program goes into
	 interactive "Copy Color" mode, requiring the user to select
	 the destination color register.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node CountColors "CountColors"

COUNTCOLORS

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      CountColors Quiet/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Count the number of unique colors in the main image buffer.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Quiet@{uu}
	 If specified, the number of colors will not be displayed onscreen
	 to the user but instead be returned in the result string.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      If "Quiet" is specified, the number of colors will be returned in the
      result variable.

@endnode

@node CreateAlpha "CreateAlpha"

CREATEALPHA

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      CreateAlpha
	 Black/S,Matte/S,Region/S,Brush/S,Waves/S,Length/N,CenterX/N,Center
	 Y/N,Angle/N,Dampen/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Create a particular type of alpha channel.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Black@{uu}
	 Create a black alpha channel.

      @{u}Matte@{uu}
	 Create an alpha channel matte based on the main image buffer.

      @{u}Region@{uu}
	 Create an alpha channel based on the currently defined region.

      @{u}Brush (2.0)@{uu}
	 Create an alpha channel composed of the current brush.

      @{u}Waves@{uu}
	 Invoke the wave generator to create the alpha channel.  The
	 following parameters deal with the type of waves to generate.

      @{u}Length@{uu}
	 Wavelength in pixels (distance between waves).

      @{u}CenterX,CenterY@{uu}
	 Center point of the waves, in buffer pixels.  Need not be visible.

      @{u}Angle@{uu}
	 Angle	of the waves.  By varying the angle over a series of
	 frames, you create moving waves.

      @{u}Dampen@{uu}
	 Wave dampening, expressed as a percentage of wave force reduction
	 per wavelength distance from the center.  Thus, a dampening of 50%
	 would have the waves losing 50% of their size every wavelength.

      Note:  Better waves can be produced with the new Wave hook.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node CreateBuffer "CreateBuffer"

CREATEBUFFER

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      CreateBuffer
	 Width/N,Height/N,Grey/S,VMem/S,Force/S,Red/N,Green/N,Blue/N,Aspect
	 X/N,AspectY/N,DPIX/N,DPIY/N,New/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Create a new empty image buffer, replacing any existing one.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Width@{uu}
	 Width of the new buffer in pixels.

      @{u}Height@{uu}
	 Height of the new buffer in pixels.

      @{u}Grey@{uu}
	 If specified, the new buffer will be greyscale (8-bit). Otherwise
	 it will be color (24-bit).

      @{u}VMem@{uu}
	 If specified, the new buffer will use virtual memory. Normally,
	 the program will attempt to allocate the buffer from RAM before
	 resorting to virtual memory.

      @{u}Force@{uu}
	 If specified, this will bypass the normal "Are you sure?"
	 requester that normally appears.

      @{u}Red,Green,Blue (2.0)@{uu}
	 Specifies the background color of the new buffer.

      @{u}AspectX,AspectY (2.0)@{uu}
	 Specifies the pixel aspect ratio of the new buffer.

      @{u}DPIX,DPIY (2.0)@{uu}
	 Specifies the DPI of the new buffer.

      @{u}New (3.0)@{uu}
	 Create a new view window for the buffer.  If not specified,
	 the current active view will be destroyed and the new buffer
	 will replace it.  This is for compatibility with older scripts.

	 (3.2) When used with the classic interface, the old main buffer
	 is pushed to the swap buffer, and the old swap buffer is stored
	 in the multiple buffer list.

      Note:  If no arguments are specified, the standard Create
	 Buffer window will be presented.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node CreateLayer "CreateLayer"

CREATELAYER (3.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      CreateLayer FromBrush/S,FromSwap/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Create a new layer in the current image.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}FromBrush@{uu}
	 The new layer is copied from the current brush.

      @{u}FromSwap@{uu}
	 The new layer is copied from the current swap buffer.

      Note:  If no arguments are specified, an empty layer
	 will be created.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node CreateNailFile "CreateNailFile"

CREATENAILFILE (2.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      CreateNailFile File/A,Depth/N,Path

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Create a thumbnail file from the main buffer and save to the given
      file.

      Note:  If thumbnail.library is not installed properly, this
	 function does nothing.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}File@{uu}
	 Name of the file to associate the thumbnail with.  Note that ".nail"
	 will be appended to the filename.  Presumably, there is already a
	 'real' image file that exists under the name "File".

      @{u}Depth@{uu}
	 Depth of the thumbnails, either 12 or 24.  Defaults to 24.

      @{u}Path (2.1a)@{uu}
	 Selects the path where the thumbnail file is actually saved.  This
	 is used when you cannot physically save a thumbnail in the same
	 directory with the image, eg. on a CD-ROM.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.


@endnode

@node Crop "Crop"

CROP

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Crop Left/N,Top/N,Width/N,Height/N,ToSwap/S,Auto/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Crop the main image buffer to the specified size.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Left,Top@{uu}
	 Upper left corner of the cropped region, given in pixel
	 coordinates.

      @{u}Width,Height@{uu}
	 Width and height of the cropped region, in pixels.

      @{u}ToSwap@{uu}
	 If specified, the cropped region will be placed into the swap
	 buffer instead of replacing the main buffer.

      @{u}Auto (2.0)@{uu}
	 Does an autocrop.

      Note:  If no arguments are given, the standard Crop window will
	 be presented.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Cyan "Cyan"

CYAN

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Cyan Adjust/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Adjust the cyan content of the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Adjust@{uu}
	 Amount to adjust the cyan (-127 to +127).

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Disperse "Disperse"

DISPERSE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Disperse Count/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform a disperse effect on the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Count@{uu}
	 Number of times to apply the dispersion (1-8).  High iterations
	 take longer to process.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Distort "Distort"

DISTORT

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Distort Amount/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform a distortion effect on the current image or region.  Note
      that this command requires an alpha channel.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Amount@{uu}
	 Amount of distortion to apply (1-255).  If not given, a requester
	 will be presented.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Dither "Dither"

DITHER

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Dither Command,Args/F

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Send a command to the current Dither module.  It is entirely up to
      the module to interpret and act upon the command.

      Note:  There are no Arexx arguments for the standard Dither
	 module.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Depends on the module.@{uu}

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Depends on the module.

@endnode

@node DrawMode "DrawMode"

DRAWMODE (2.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      DrawMode Name,Options/S,Args/F

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Change or set arguments for the current drawmode.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Name@{uu}
	 Name of the new drawmode to change to.  If not provided, the
	 drawmode is not changed.

      @{u}Options@{uu}
	 Show the options window for the current drawmode, if the current
	 drawmode has any options.

      @{u}Args@{uu}
	 Arguments to be passed to the new drawmode.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the name of the previous drawmode.

@endnode

@node DrawStyle "DrawStyle"

DRAWSTYLE (2.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      DrawStyle Name,Options/S,Args/F

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Change or set the parameters for the current drawstyle.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Name@{uu}
	 Name of the new drawstyle to change to.  If not provided, the
	 drawstyle is not changed.

      @{u}Options@{uu}
	 Show the options window for the current drawstyle, if the current
	 drawstyle has any options.

      @{u}Args@{uu}
	 Arguments to be passed to the new drawstyle.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the name of the previous drawstyle.

@endnode

@node DrawTool "DrawTool"

DRAWTOOL

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      DrawTool Tool

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Set the current drawing tool.  Updates the display if appropriate.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Tool@{uu}
	 Name of the drawing tool to activate.	Should be one of the
	 following choices:

	    AIRBRUSH	BEZIER	    BOX 	FILLEDBOX
	    FILLEDFREE	FILLEDOVAL  FILLEDPOLY	FLOOD
	    FREEDRAW	FREELINE    LINE	OVAL
	    POLY
	    LAYERMOVE (3.0)

      Note:  If no arguments are specified, no change is made.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the name of the active drawing tool before any changes are
      made.

@endnode

@node DynamicRange "DynamicRange"

DYNAMICRANGE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      DynamicRange Lower/N,Upper/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform a dynamic range effect on the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Lower@{uu}
	 Lower color limit (0-255).

      @{u}Upper@{uu}
	 Upper color limit (0-255).

      Note:  If no arguments are given, the standard dynamic range
	 requester is presented.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node EdgeDetect "EdgeDetect"

EDGEDETECT

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      EdgeDetect Threshold/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform an edge detect function on the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Threshold@{uu}
	 Detection threshold (1-255).  The smaller the number, the more
	 pronounced the edges.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node EdgeMode "EdgeMode"

EDGEMODE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      EdgeMode Mode,Radius/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Change and/or get information on the current the edge mode.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Mode@{uu}
	 New edge mode.  Should be a single case-insensitive word:

	 Normal AntiAlias FeatherIn FeatherOut
      @{u}Radius@{uu}
	 For "FeatherIn" and "FeatherOut" modes, this describes the radius
	 of the effect, in pixels.

      Note:  If no arguments are given, no change is made.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Previous edge mode and radius, before the change, in the form of
      "EdgeMode Radius".

@endnode

@node EndBar "EndBar"

ENDBAR

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      EndBar

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Complete a status bar operation.	Returns control of the program to
      the user, clears the "busy" pointer.

      You should ALWAYS remember to follow any calls to BeginBar with an
      eventual call to EndBar.	The user will not be able to click on any
      gadgets until you do.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      BeginBar,Bar

@endnode

@node ExpandRegion "ExpandRegion"

EXPANDREGION

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      ExpandRegion

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Expand the current region area by a pixel on all sides.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      ShrinkRegion

@endnode

@node ExportBuffer "ExportBuffer"

EXPORTBUFFER

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      ExportBuffer

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Indicate that you are finished using a buffer that was created using
      the ImportBuffer command.  You MUST call this when you are done,
      otherwise bad things may happen.

      WARNING:	This is a very dangerous command.  Don't use it
	 lightly.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      ImportBuffer

@endnode

@node FalseColor "FalseColor"

FALSECOLOR

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      FalseColor Standard/S,Palette/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform a false color effect on the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Standard@{uu}
	 Uses the standard table for creating false color images.

      @{u}Palette@{uu}
	 Uses the current palette for generating the false color image.

      Note:  If no option is specified, a requester will be presented
	 to ask for standard or palette.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node FilledBox "FilledBox"

FILLEDBOX

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      FilledBox Left/N,Top/N,Width/N,Height/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Draw a filled box into the current image buffer at the given
      location, using the current fill settings.  If Scissors or
      MagicScissors has been activated, this will cut out the area defined
      by the box as a brush.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Left,Top@{uu}
	 Upper left corner of the box, in pixels.

      @{u}Width,Height@{uu}
	 Width and height of the box, in pixels.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node FilledFree "FilledFree"

FILLEDFREE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      FilledFree

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Draw a filled freehand polygon into the main buffer, using the
      current fill settings.  The points defining the freehand outline is
      set by calls to NewArea/AddArea.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      NewArea,AddArea

@endnode

@node FilledOval "FilledOval"

FILLEDOVAL

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      FilledOval XC/N,YC/N,XRadius/N,YRadius/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Draw a filled oval into the current image buffer, using the current
      fill settings.  If Scissors or MagicScissors has been specified, the
      area defined by the oval will be picked up as a brush.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}XC,YC@{uu}
	 Coordinates of the center point of the oval, in pixels.

      @{u}XRadius,YRadius@{uu}
	 Major and minor radii of the oval, in pixels.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node FilledPoly "FilledPoly"

FILLEDPOLY

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      FilledPoly

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Draw a filled polygon into the main buffer, using the current drawing
      color and fill settings.	The points of the polygon are defined by
      calls to NewArea/AddArea.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      NewArea,AddArea

@endnode

@node FillMode "FillMode"

FILLMODE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      FillMode Mode,Range/N,Skew/N,Rough/N,Smooth/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Select the current fill settings, which are used for all subsequent
      filling operations.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Mode@{uu}
	 New fill type.  Should be one of the following choices:

	 Solid Vert Horiz Radial DiagLR DiagRL Tile Warp Brick Wheel
      @{u}Range@{uu}
	 For gradient fill types, this specifies the range number from
	 which to take the colors for the gradient.  Should be 0-8, with
	 range 0 being taken as the ALL range (the entire palette).

      @{u}Skew@{uu}
	 Amount of skew to apply to gradient fills (-50 to +50).

      @{u}Rough@{uu}
	 Roughness to add to any fill operation (1-31).

      @{u}Smooth@{uu}
	 If selected, gradient fills will automatically smooth between the
	 colors in the selected range.	Otherwise, the colors in the range
	 are used literally with no smoothing between them (resulting in
	 bands of color).

      Note:  If no arguments are given, no changes are made.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the current fill settings before any changes are made, in the
      form "mode range skew rough smooth".

@endnode

@node FitWindow "FitWindow"

FITWINDOW (3.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      FitWindow

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Resize the current image window to fit the buffer it represents.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node FlattenLayers "FlattenLayers"

FLATTENLAYERS (3.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      FlattenLayers

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Flatten all the layers of the current buffer into a single
      layer.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node FloodFill "FloodFill"

FLOODFILL

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      FloodFill X/N/A,Y/N/A,Close/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Flood fill an area using the current drawing color, starting at the
      given buffer coordinates.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}X,Y@{uu}
	 Coordinates at which to begin the flood fill.

      @{u}Close@{uu}
	 Optional flood closeness (1-255).

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node FloodRegion "FloodRegion"

FLOODREGION

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      FloodRegion Add/S,Subtract/S,X/N/A,Y/N/A,Close/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Define a region in the main buffer by doing a flood fill at a given
      location.  Subsequent image processing operations will be constrained
      to this region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Add@{uu}
	 If specified, this region is to be merged in with the existing
	 region.  Otherwise the new region supercedes any existing regions.

      @{u}Subtract (2.0)@{uu}
	 If specified, this region will be subtracted from the existing
	 region.

      @{u}X,Y@{uu}
	 Location from which to do the flood fill.

      @{u}Close@{uu}
	 Optional closeness value to use in the flood fill operation.  If
	 not specified, the current default will be used.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node FreeDraw "FreeDraw"

FREEDRAW

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      FreeDraw

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Draw into the main buffer using the freehand drawing tool.  The path
      the drawing follows is defined by calls to NewArea/AddArea.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      NewArea,AddArea

@endnode

@node FreeLine "FreeLine"

FREELINE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      FreeLine

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Draw into the main buffer using the freehand line tool.  The path the
      drawing follows is defined by calls to NewArea/AddArea.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      NewArea,AddArea

@endnode

@node Gamma "Gamma"

GAMMA

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Gamma Adjust/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Adjust the gamma of the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Adjust@{uu}
	 Amount to adjust the gamma (-127 to +127).

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node GetAlpha "GetAlpha"

GETALPHA

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetAlpha

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Return information about the alpha channel.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns a string containing information about the alpha channel.

      See @{" GetMain " link GetMain } for the format of the result string.

      A null (empty) string is returned if the alpha channel is empty.

@endnode

@node GetBufferList "GetBufferList"

GETBUFFERLIST (3.2)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetBufferList

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Returns information about all available buffers in memory.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the following string variables:

	 RESULT.0
	    The number of available buffers.

      For each available buffer, the following string variables
      are set:

	 RESULT.x.NAME
	    The name of the buffer.  This name can be used to select
	    the buffer, or use it in some other way.

	 RESULT.x.SIZE
	    A series of numbers delimited by spaces describing the
	    size and characteristics of the buffer, similar to the
	    results returned by GetMain.  The attributes returned
	    are:

	       width height depth aspectx aspecty dpix dpiy
	       hastransp numcolors numlayers

@endnode

@node GetBrush "GetBrush"

GETBRUSH

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetBrush

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Return information about the current brush.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns a string containing information about the current brush.

      See @{" GetMain " link GetMain } for the format of the result string.

      A null (empty) string is returned if there is no brush.

@endnode

@node GetLayers "GetLayers"

GETLAYERS (3.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetLayers

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Return the number of layers in the current image.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the number of layers in the image, including the background
      layer.  If the image is not layered, a non-zero return code is
      generated.

@endnode

@node GetMain "GetMain"

GETMAIN

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetMain

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Return information about the main buffer.

      Information is returned about the active layer in the buffer.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns a string containing information about the current buffer, in
      the following format:

	 "name" width height depth aspectx aspecty dpix dpiy
	    redp greenp bluep
	    transp numcolors layers

      A null (empty) string is returned if the buffer is empty.

      @{u}name@{uu}
	 Filename of the buffer, surrounded by quotes.

      @{u}width, height, depth@{uu}
	 Width, height, and number of byte planes in the buffer.  Byte planes
	 will always be either 1 or 3.

      @{u}aspectx, aspecty@{uu}
	 Pixel aspect ratio of the image buffer.

      @{u}dpix, dpiy@{uu}
	 Pixels per inch, horizontally and vertically, of the image buffer.

      @{u}redp, greenp, bluep@{uu}
	 Pointers to the physical image data of the buffer.  DO NOT USE THIS
	 UNLESS YOU KNOW WHAT YOU ARE DOING.

      @{u}transp@{uu} (3.0)
	 1 if the image has a transparency plane (alpha channel) or 0 if
	 it does not.

      @{u}numcolors@{uu} (3.0)
	 If the image is a colormapped image, this will contain the number
	 of valid colors in the colormap (usually 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64, 128
	 or 256).  Otherwise it will be 0 for a greyscale or RGB image.

      @{u}layers@{uu} (3.0)
	 Number of layers in the entire buffer.

@endnode

@node GetPalette "GetPalette"

GETPALETTE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetPalette Register/N/A

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Retrieve the color value of a specified color register in the current
      palette.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Register@{uu}
	 Register to look at, should be in the range 0 - 255 or '-1', to
	 get the color of the current active register.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Color value of the register, in the form "R G B" where each component
      is an integer in the range of 0 - 255.

@endnode

@node GetPixel "GetPixel"

GETPIXEL

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetPixel X/N/A,Y/N/A

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Read the color value of a pixel at a given location.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}X,Y@{uu}
	 Coordinates of the pixel to read, in buffer pixels.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the RGB value of the given pixel, in the form "Red Green
      Blue", where each component is an integer from 0-255.  In the case of
      a greyscale buffer, all three components will be the same.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
   PutPixel
@endnode

@node GetPointList "GetPointList"

GETPOINTLIST

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetPointList

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Returns in a stem variable the points in the currently defined area
      as set by calls to NewArea/AddArea.  The points may also be set by
      the user's use of certain drawing tools (FreeDraw, FreeLine, etc.).

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the list of points in RESULT.1 through RESULT.N.	RESULT.0 is
      set to the number of points.  Each point is given as integers in the
      form "X Y".

@endnode

@node GetPrefs "GetPrefs"

GETPREFS

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetPrefs Object/A

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Retrieve the state of a certain preferences object.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Object@{uu}
	 Which preference item you want to get information on.	It should
	 be a single case-sensitive word.

	 For a list of the available preferences objects, see the
	 description of the @{" SETPREFS " link SetPrefs } command.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Depends on the preference object; for flags the result will be either
      "On" or "Off", for path objects, the result string will contain the
      path.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      SetPrefs

@endnode

@node GetPreview "GetPreview"

GETPREVIEW

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetPreview

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Returns the current preview module.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the name of the current preview module.

@endnode

@node GetPrinter "GetPrinter"

GETPRINTER

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetPrinter

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Returns the current printer module.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the name of the current printer module.

@endnode

@node GetRange "GetRange"

GETRANGE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetRange Range/N/A

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Retrieve the upper and lower register boundaries of a given color
      range.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Range@{uu}
	 Range number to examine, 1 - 8.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Lower and upper registers in the range, expressed as integers in the
      form "Low High".

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      SetRange

@endnode

@node GetRegionArea "GetRegionArea"

GETREGIONAREA

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetRegionArea

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Returns the area covered by the currently defined region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the region in the following form: "leftedge topedge width
      height"

@endnode

@node GetRender "GetRender"

GETRENDER

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetRender

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Return the current render module.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the name of the current render module.

@endnode

@node GetScanner "GetScanner"

GETSCANNER

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetScanner

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Return the current scanner module.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the name of the current scanner module.

@endnode

@node GetStatus "GetStatus"

GETSTATUS (2.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetStatus Object/A

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Return information about the current status of ImageFX.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Object@{uu}
	 The name of an ImageFX attribute to obtain information about.	The
	 following attributes are defined:

      @{u}  ProgramDir	   Full pathname of ImageFX’s current@{uu}
			directory.
      @{u}  HelpDir	   Full pathname of the directory where help@{uu}
			text is stored.
      @{u}  TextDir	   Full pathname of the directory where@{uu}
			localization text is stored.
      @{u}  EnvDir	   Directory in ENV: where ImageFX’s@{uu}
			environment variables are stored.
      @{u}  PubScrName	   Name of ImageFX’s public screen (if open@{uu}
			on a screen).
      @{u}  HostName	   Name of ImageFX’s Arexx port (if@{uu}
			available).
      @{u}  AssignDir	   Assign name of the ImageFX directory.@{uu}

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns a text string as described above.

@endnode

@node GetSwap "GetSwap"

GETSWAP

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetSwap

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Return information about the swap buffer.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns a string containing information about the swap buffer.

      See @{" GetMain " link GetMain } for the format of the result string.

      A null (empty) string is returned if the swap buffer is empty.

@endnode

@node GetVersion "GetVersion"

GETVERSION

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GetVersion

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Return the version string for the program.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Version string in the standard 2.0 version string format.

@endnode

@node GhostBrush "GhostBrush"

GHOSTBRUSH

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GhostBrush On/S,Off/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Enable or disable the "ghost brush" feature on the current brush.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}On@{uu}
	 Enable ghost brush; the current brush will be made semi-
	 transparent.

      @{u}Off@{uu}
	 Disable ghost brush; the current brush will be shown normally.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node GrabBrush "GrabBrush"

GRABBRUSH

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GrabBrush ScreenName

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Capture an Amiga screen as the current brush.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}ScreenName@{uu}
	 If specified, indicates the name of a screen to grab.	You do not
	 have to specify the entire screen name, just enough to distinguish
	 it from other screens.

      Note:  If no arguments are specified, the standard Grab Screen
	 requester is presented.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node GrabBuffer "GrabBuffer"

GRABBUFFER

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GrabBuffer ScreenName,Force/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Capture an Amiga screen and convert into an image buffer.  The screen
      image will become the new main buffer, destroying whatever may have
      been there.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}ScreenName@{uu}
	 If specified, indicates the name of a screen to grab.	You do not
	 have to specify the entire screen name, just enough to distinguish
	 it from other screens.

      @{u}Force@{uu}
	 Bypass the normal "Are you sure?" requester.

      Note:  If no arguments are specified, the standard "Grab
	 Screen" requester will be presented.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node GrabPalette "GrabPalette"

GRABPALETTE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      GrabPalette ScreenName

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Grab the colors from an Amiga screen in memory, storing it into the
      first entries of the current palette.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}ScreenName@{uu}
	 Name of the screen to examine.  If not given, the standard Grab
	 Screen requester will be presented.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Green "Green"

GREEN

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Green Adjust/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Adjust the green content of the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Adjust@{uu}
	 Amount to adjust the green (-127 to +127).  This number is added
	 directly to each green value.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Grey2Color "Grey2Color"

GREY2COLOR

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Grey2Color
      Gray2Color (1.50)
      GreyToColor (1.50)
      GrayToColor (1.50)

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Convert an 8-bit grey image to 24-bit color.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Grid "Grid"

GRID

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Grid On/S,Off/S,OffsetX/N,OffsetY/N,Width/N,Height/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Enable or disable the grid, and set the size of the grid in pixels.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}On@{uu}
	 Turn on the grid.  (2.0)

      @{u}Off@{uu}
	 Turn off the grid.

      @{u}OffsetX,OffsetY@{uu}
	 Grid offset from the upper left corner of the display, given in
	 pixels.

      @{u}Width,Height@{uu}
	 Grid block size in pixels.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the state of the grid before any changes are made, as
      integers in the form "offsetx offsety width height ON|OFF".

@endnode

@node Halftone "Halftone"

HALFTONE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Halftone Type/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Apply one of several types of halftone dithering algorithms to the
      current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Type@{uu}
	 Type of halftone to apply.  Should be one of the following values:

	 0	 45 degree cluster
	    1	      0 degree cluster
	    2	      Spiral cluster
	    3	      Line cluster
	    4	      (Unused)
	    5	      4x4 dispersed
	    6	      6x6 dispersed
	    7	      Use brush as pattern
	    8	      Use alpha channel as pattern
	    9	      50% threshold

      Note:  If no arguments are given, a requester will be
	 presented.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Help "Help"

HELP

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Help Command/A,Quiet/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Obtain the argument template for a specified command.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Command@{uu}
	 The name of the command to retreive help on.

      @{u}Quiet  (2.0)@{uu}
	 When specified, simply prints the template for the command to the
	 console (or returns it in @{b}RESULT).  Otherwise, an AmigaGuide node@{ub}
	 containing the command will be searched for.

   RESULT
      Returns the argument template string for the specified command.

@endnode

@node HidePanel "HidePanel"

HIDEPANEL

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      HidePanel

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Hide the ImageFX menu panel screen.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      ShowPanel

@endnode

@node Hook "Hook"

HOOK

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Hook File,Args/F

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Call an external hook program.  This command will not return until
      the hook program has finished.  Consult the documentation for the
      hook program in question to find out the appropriate arguments and
      possible result strings.

      See the @{" ImageFX Hook Arexx Reference " link Arexx_Hooks.guide/Main } for more details.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}File@{uu}
	 Filename of the hook program to run.  If not specified, a file
	 requester will be presented.

      @{u}Args@{uu}
	 Optional arguments to pass to the hook program.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Depends on the hook program.

@endnode

@node HorizFlip "HorizFlip"

HORIZFLIP

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      HorizFlip

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform a horizontal flip on the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      VertFlip

@endnode

@node HorizMirror "HorizMirror"

HORIZMIRROR

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      HorizMirror

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform a horizontal mirror effect on the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Hue "Hue"

HUE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Hue Adjust/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Adjust the hue of the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Adjust@{uu}
	 Amount to adjust the hue (-127 to +127).

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Iconify "Iconify"

ICONIFY

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Iconify

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Iconify the program.  All buffers remain intact.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      Uniconify

@endnode

@node ImageMap "ImageMap"

IMAGEMAP (OBSOLETE)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      ImageMap Blend/N,Alpha/S,Scale/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform an image mapping composition process between the main and
      swap buffers.  This function is still provided for backwards
      compatibility; see the Composite hook for greater image composition
      control.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Blend@{uu}
	 Percentage of image mapping applied to the main buffer (1-100).

      @{u}Alpha@{uu}
	 If given, uses the alpha channel as an extra blend control plane.

      @{u}Scale@{uu}
	 If given, the swap buffer is scaled to fit within the region being
	 processed.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node ImportBuffer "ImportBuffer"

IMPORTBUFFER

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      ImportBuffer Width/N/A,Height/N/A,Red/N/A,Green/N/A,Blue/N/A

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Directly import a block of image data memory into the program as an
      image buffer.  Basically sets up an image buffer in the program which
      points to the block of memory you indicate.  A copy is NOT made of
      the image data.  This would (theoretically) allow one to use
      ImageFX’s image processing features on image data from other
      programs.

      WARNING:	This is a very dangerous command.  Don't use it
	 lightly.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Width,Height@{uu}
	 Size of the image data in pixels.

      @{u}Red,Green,Blue@{uu}
	 Red, green, and blue plane pointers.  Each should be an integer
	 representing the address in memory of where the particular pointer
	 is.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      ExportBuffer

@endnode

@node InvertRegion "InvertRegion"

INVERTREGION

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      InvertRegion

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Inverts the currently defined region mask.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node KillAll "KillAll"

KILLALL (2.1)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      KillAll

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Erase all image buffers from memory.  This is identical to selecting
      the Delete All Buffers from the Buffers menu.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node KillAlpha "KillAlpha"

KILLALPHA

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      KillAlpha

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Delete the transparency channel (alpha channel) associated with
      the current buffer.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node KillBrush "KillBrush"

KILLBRUSH

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      KillBrush Name

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Erase the current brush, freeing all memory associated with it.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Name (2.1)@{uu}
	 Specifies the name of the brush you want to delete.  If
	 not provided, the current brush is deleted.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node KillBuffer "KillBuffer"

KILLBUFFER

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      KillBuffer Name,Force/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Erase the main image buffer, freeing all memory associated with it.
      You cannot get it back after doing this.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Name (2.1)@{uu}
	 Specifies the name of the image buffer you want to delete.  If
	 not provided, the main image buffer is deleted.

      @{u}Force@{uu}
	 If specified, the normal "Are you sure?" requester is bypassed.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node KillLayer "KillLayer"

KILLLAYER (3.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      KillLayer

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Delete the active layer.	Note that you cannot delete the
      background layer.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node KillMapped "KillMapped"

KILLMAPPED (2.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      KillMapped

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Free the memory used by any colormapped images loaded with
      LoadMapped.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node KillSwap "KillSwap"

KILLSWAP

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      KillSwap Force/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Erase the swap buffer, freeing all memory associated with it.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Force@{uu}
	 If given, bypasses the "are you sure?" requester.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node KillUndo "KillUndo"

KILLUNDO

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      KillUndo

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Free the memory associated with the current undo buffer.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node LayerBlend "LayerBlend"

LAYERBLEND (3.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LayerBlend Blend/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Set the blending for the active layer.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Blend@{uu}
	 New blending value, from 0 to 255.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the previous blending value, before the change.

@endnode

@node LayerMode "LayerMode"

LAYERMODE (3.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LayerMode Mode,Mask/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Change the composite mode for the active layer.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Mode@{uu}
	 New compositing mode for the layer.  Select from one of the
	 following keywords:
	    NORMAL	    DARKEN	    LIGHTEN
	    ADD 	    SUBTRACT	    MULTIPLY
	    DIVIDE	    SUM 	    DIFFERENCE
	    MINIMUM	    MAXIMUM	    AND
	    OR		    XOR 	    SCREEN
	    ILLUMINATE	    COLORIZE	    SOFTLIGHT
	    HARDLIGHT

      @{u}Mask@{uu}
	 Changes the layer into a "mask" layer.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the previous mode, before the change.

@endnode

@node LayerName "LayerName"

LAYERNAME (3.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LayerName Name

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Change the name of the active layer.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Name@{uu}
	 The new name for the layer.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the previous layer name, before the change.

@endnode

@node LayerOffset "LayerOffset"

LAYEROFFSET (3.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LayerOffset X/N,Y/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Change the position of the active layer.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}X, Y@{uu}
	 New offset position for the active layer.  An offset of
	 0, 0 positions the layer at the upper left corner of the
	 background layer.  Negative offsets move the image up and
	 to the left, while positive offsets move it down and to
	 the right.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the previous X & Y offset, before the change.

@endnode

@node Learn "Learn"

LEARN

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Learn File,Stop/S,NoHeader/S,Header/S,Quiet/S,Force/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Control ImageFX’s macro recording feature (aka. “learning”).

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}File@{uu}
	 The name of an Arexx program to generate.  If no name is given, a
	 file requester will be presented.  The extension of “.ifx” is
	 automatically appended if not provided.

      @{u}Stop@{uu}
	 Stop recording and close the Arexx program file.

      @{u}NoHeader, Header@{uu}
	 Specify whether or not to write the current drawing information.
	 If neither is specified, then a requester is presented to the
	 user.

      @{u}Quiet@{uu}
	 Specify this to disable the “macro recording stopped” requester.

      @{u}Force@{uu}
	 Specify this to force overwriting existing files without prompting
	 the user.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node LightTable "LightTable"

LIGHTTABLE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LightTable On/S,Off/S,Toggle/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Enable or disable the light table mode.  Light table mode allows you
      to see the swap buffer through the main buffer.  Both buffers must be
      the same size for this to work.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}On,Off@{uu}
	 Enable or disable the light table mode.

      @{u}Toggle@{uu}
	 Toggle the state of the light table mode.

      Note:  If no arguments are given, then no change is made.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the state of the light table mode before any changes are
      made.

@endnode

@node LightTableView "LightTableView"

LIGHTTABLEVIEW

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LightTableView Swap/S,Alpha/S,Toggle/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Select the buffer that the light table shows through.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Swap@{uu}
	 When selected, the light table will show the swap buffer.

      @{u}Alpha@{uu}
	 When selected, the light table will show the alpha channel.

      @{u}Toggle@{uu}
	 Toggles between the two views.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the former light table view, "Swap" or "Alpha".

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      LightTable

@endnode

@node Line "Line"

LINE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Line X1/N,Y1/N,X2/N,Y2/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Draw a line at the given location in the current image buffer, using
      the current drawing pen or brush, and all of the current drawing
      settings.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}X1,Y1@{uu}
	 Starting coordinates of the line.

      @{u}X2,Y2@{uu}
	 Ending coordinates of the line.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node ListRequest "ListRequest"

LISTREQUEST

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      ListRequest Count/N/A,Stem/A

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Present a pop-up vertical list requester to the user, similar to the
      type that the program uses in the toolbox.  The user must choose one
      of the selections before proceeding, or hit cancel.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Count@{uu}
	 Number of gadgets to appear in the requester, plus one for the
	 title entry.

      @{u}Stem@{uu}
	 Stem variable where the gadget labels are stored.  The first label
	 is taken to be the title for the requester, thus the first
	 gadget's label should be in Stem.2, the second label in Stem.3,
	 the third in Stem.4, and so on.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the number of the gadget the user chose, from 1 - N, if
      successful.

@endnode

@node LoadAlpha "LoadAlpha"

LOADALPHA

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LoadAlpha File,Args/F

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}


   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}File@{uu}
	 Filename of the image to load.  If not specified, a file requester
	 will be presented.

      @{u}Args@{uu}
	 Optional arguments passed to the Loader module.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node LoadBrush "LoadBrush"

LOADBRUSH

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LoadBrush File,Args/F

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Load an image as a brush, destroying the old brush.  The program will
      automatically determine the format of the file being loaded and call
      the appropriate Loader module.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}File@{uu}
	 Filename of the image to load.  If not specified, a file requester
	 will be presented.  If a full pathname is not given, the file is
	 assumed to be in the current brush load path (as set in prefs).

      @{u}Args@{uu}
	 Passed to the Loader module that gets called.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node LoadBrushClip "LoadBrushClip"

LOADBRUSHCLIP

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LoadBrushClip

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Load the image in the clipboard in as the current brush, destroying
      the previous brush.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node LoadBuffer "LoadBuffer"

LOADBUFFER

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LoadBuffer File,Force/S,New/S,Args/F

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Load an image into the main buffer, destroying the old contents.
      ImageFX will automatically determine the format of the file being
      loaded and call the appropriate Loader module.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}File@{uu}
	 Pathname of the image to load.  If a full path is not given, then
	 the file is assumed to reside in the current Load path (as set in
	 prefs).

      @{u}Force@{uu}
	 Bypass the normal "Are you sure?" requester.

      @{u}New (3.0)@{uu}
	 Create a new view window for the buffer.  If not specified,
	 the current active view will be destroyed and the new buffer
	 will replace it.  This is for compatibility with older scripts.

	 (3.2) When used with the classic interface, the old main buffer
	 is pushed to the swap buffer, and the old swap buffer is stored
	 in the multiple buffer list.

      @{u}Args@{uu}
	 Passed to the loader module that gets used.  For example, you can
	 pass the exact frame number you want to load to the ANIM loader.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node LoadBufferAs "LoadBufferAs"

LOADBUFFERAS

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LoadBufferAs Format,File,Force/S,New/S,Args/F

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Force the program to load a file using a specified file format. This
      can be used if a particular file format (such as the Sculpt RGB
      format) cannot be automatically detected for some reason.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Format@{uu}
	 File format to load as.  If not specified, a file format requester
	 will be presented.

      @{u}File@{uu}
	 Name of the file to load.  If not specified, a file requester will
	 be presented.	If a full path is not given, the file is assumed to
	 reside in the current load path (as set in prefs).

      @{u}Force@{uu}
	 If specified, bypass the normal "are you sure?" requester.

      @{u}New (3.0)@{uu}
	 Create a new view window for the buffer.  If not specified,
	 the current active view will be destroyed and the new buffer
	 will replace it.  This is for compatibility with older scripts.

      @{u}Args@{uu}
	 Arguments passed to the loader module.  See the documentation for
	 the particular loader module.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node LoadBufferClip "LoadBufferClip"

LOADBUFFERCLIP

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LoadBufferClip Force/S,New/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Load the image in the clipboard into the main image buffer.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Force@{uu}
	 If specified, bypasses the normal "are you sure?" requester.

      @{u}New@{uu} (3.1b)
	 Creates a new view window for the new image.  Otherwise the
	 current image is overwritten to preserve backwards compatibility.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node LoadLayer "LoadLayer"

LOADLAYER (3.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LoadLayer File,Args/F

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Load a file from disk and create a new layer out of it.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}File@{uu}
	 Name of the file to load.  If not specified, a file requester will
	 be presented.

      @{u}Args@{uu}
	 Arguments to be passed to the loader module.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node LoadMapped "LoadMapped"

LOADMAPPED (2.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LoadMapped File,Args/F

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Load a file from disk directly as a colormapped image.  The image may
      then be saved immediately using the SaveRenderedAs command, without
      having to render.  This command is ideally suited for converting
      colormapped images from one format to another.

      Note that you should follow any LoadMapped commands with an eventual
      call to KillMapped to free the memory used by the colormapped image.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}File@{uu}
	 Name of the file to load.  If not specified, a file requester will
	 be presented.

      @{u}Args@{uu}
	 Arguments to be passed to the loader module.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node LoadMask "LoadMask"

LOADMASK (2.0)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LoadMask File,Add/S,Subtract/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Load a mask file from disk and make it the current region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}File@{uu}
	 Name of the file to load.  If not provided, a file requester will
	 be presented.

      @{u}Add@{uu}
	 If specified, the new mask will be added to the current region to
	 combine the two masks.

      @{u}Subtract@{uu}
	 If specified, the new mask will be subtracted from the current
	 region.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      SaveMaskAs

@endnode

@node LoadPalette "LoadPalette"

LOADPALETTE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LoadPalette File,Number/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Load colors from the given file into the current palette.  May also
      load range definitions, depending on the file format.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}File@{uu}
	 Name of the file to read colors from.	If not given, a file
	 requester will be presented.  If a full path is not given, the
	 file is assumed to be in the current Palette path (as set by
	 prefs).

      @{u}Number (1.50)@{uu}
	 Palette number to load into.  -1 to load into the currently
	 displayed palette, or a palette number from 1 - 8.  (Palette
	 number 8 is the render palette.)

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node LockGui "LockGui"

LOCKGUI

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LockGui

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Prevents the program from drawing or refreshing anything on the menu
      display, including gadgets, mode indicators, etc.  This is extremely
      useful when performing a long series of operations which would
      normally update corresponding gadgets on the display at each step.
      Disabling the gadget refreshing can considerably speed up the
      operation in question.  This command will also disable the status bar
      completely, as well as preview redrawing.

      You are wise to follow this command with an eventual call to
      UnlockGui, to return things to normal.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node LockInput "LockInput"

LOCKINPUT

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LockInput

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Prevent the user from clicking on any gadgets.  This is useful if you
      don't want the user messing with things while your Arexx script is
      running.	Be sure to eventually follow this with a call to
      UnlockInput to restore things to normal.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
      UnlockInput

@endnode

@node LockRange "LockRange"

LOCKRANGE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      LockRange Range/N/A,On/S,Off/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Lock or unlock the given palette range.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Range@{uu}
	 Palette range to affect (0-8).  Range 0 indicates you want to
	 affect the entire palette.

      @{u}On@{uu}
	 Lock the given range.

      @{u}Off@{uu}
	 Unlock the given range.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Magenta "Magenta"

MAGENTA

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Magenta Adjust/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Adjust the magenta content of the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Adjust@{uu}
	 Amount to adjust the magenta (-127 to +127).

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node MagicCycle "MagicCycle"

MAGICCYCLE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      MagicCycle

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Cycles to the next application that has opened the MAGIC image in the
      main buffer.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node MagicOpen "MagicOpen"

MAGICOPEN

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      MagicOpen Name,Force/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Open a selected MAGIC image for processing within ImageFX.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Name@{uu}
	 Name of the MAGIC image to open.  If not specified, a requester
	 will be presented from which the user can choose one of the
	 current MAGIC images in memory.

      @{u}Force/S@{uu}
	 Disables the "are you sure you want to overwrite the current
	 buffer" requester.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node MagicScissors "MagicScissors"

MAGICSCISSORS

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      MagicScissors

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Initiate a brush cut operation.  Issuing this command places the
      program into brush cut mode; you must then follow with a standard
      drawing command to cut out a brush in that shape.  This command
      differs from Scissors in that it uses the special “magic” scissors
      mode which will attempt to trim the background area from the brush as
      it is picked up.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Matte "Matte"

MATTE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Matte Red/N,Green/N,Blue/N,Alpha/S,Scale/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform a composite matte operation between the main and swap
      buffers.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Red,Green,Blue@{uu}
	 The color value to be taken as transparent in the main buffer.

      @{u}Alpha@{uu}
	 If specified, the alpha channel will be used as extra control in
	 the composite operation.

      @{u}Scale@{uu}
	 If specified, the swap buffer will be scaled to the size of the
	 main buffer region affected.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Menu "Menu"

MENU

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Menu Name

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Jump to the specified action menu.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Name@{uu}
	 Name of the action menu to enter, must be one of the following:

	 Scanner Palette Toolbox Render Printer
      Note:  If no menu is specified, no change is made.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Returns the name of the current action menu, before the change.

@endnode

@node Merge "Merge"

MERGE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Merge Blend/N,Alpha/S,Scale/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform a composite merge operation between the main and swap
      buffers.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Blend@{uu}
	 Percentage of blend (1-100).  Higher percentages will blend in
	 more of the swap buffer.

      @{u}Alpha@{uu}
	 If specified, the alpha channel will be used in the composite
	 operation.

      @{u}Scale@{uu}
	 If specified, the swap buffer will be scaled to the size of the
	 main buffer's region.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Message "Message"

MESSAGE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Message Text/F

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Display a message in the Arexx status window.  If the macro was
      lauched asynchronously or without the status window, then this
      command has no effect.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Text@{uu}
	 Text of the message.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Mono2Grey "Mono2Grey"

MONO2GREY

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Mono2Grey Area/N
      Mono2Gray Area/N	(1.50)
      MonoToGrey Area/N  (1.50)
      MonoToGray Area/N  (1.50)

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Convert monochrome image data to 8-bit greyscale.

