      None.


@endnode

@node ReadPixels "ReadPixels"

READPIXELS (AREXX ONLY)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      ReadPixels Var/A,Row/N/A,Width/N,LeftEdge/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      This function will directly read a block of pixels from a specified
      scanline of the Main buffer.  This can only be used from Arexx, as it
      requires a variable in which to store the results.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Var@{uu}
	 Specifies the name of the Arexx variable in which to store the
	 resulting pixel information.  The information is stored as a byte-
	 packed string of digits in the order “RGBRGBRGB...”; for example
	 ‘FF0000 00FF00 0000FF’x would be three pixels of bright red,
	 green, and blue respectively.	When reading from a greyscale
	 buffer, only one byte per pixel is stored; thus ‘FF 00 40’x would
	 be 3 pixels of high, medium, and low intensity grey.  Be careful
	 that Arexx does not expard you variable name; you must enclose it
	 in quotes within the Arexx program like this:

	 ReadPixels 'MYVAR' 0 320 0
	    newpixels = REVERSE(myvar)
	    /* etc.... */


	 You should always specify the variable in upper case, as all
	 variables are converted to upper case by Arexx.

      @{u}Row@{uu}
	 Scanline of the image from which to read pixel information.
	 Scanlines are numbered starting with 0 at the top and going down
	 to Height-1 at the bottom.  An error will be returned if you try
	 to read outside the bounds of the main buffer.

      @{u}Width@{uu}
	 Number of pixels to read from the specified scanline.	If not
	 specified, the entire width of the scanline is read.

      @{u}LeftEdge@{uu}
	 How far from the left edge of the image to start reading.  This
	 value should range from 0 (at the leftmost edge) to the width of
	 the image minus 1.  If not specified, a left offset of 0 is used.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      Pixel information will be returned in the variable specified, in the
      format detailed above.

@endnode

@node Red "Red"

RED

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Red Adjust/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Adjust the red content of the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Adjust@{uu}
	 Amount to adjust the red (-127 to +127).  This number is added
	 directly to each red value.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Redo "Redo"

REDO

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Redo

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Redo the last operation performed.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Redraw "Redraw"

REDRAW

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Redraw On/S,Off/S,Left/N,Top/N,Width/N,Height/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Redraw some or all of the main image buffer.  Also used to control
      the automatic redrawing function.  Automatic redraw will redraw the
      portion of the screen that was affected by an operation as soon as
      the operation is completed.  You may want to turn this feature off
      when performing a long series of functions to speed the operation up,
      the redraw the screen when the operations are finished.

      Redrawing the screen includes re-rendering the current brush (if
      any).

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}On@{uu}
	 Enable automatic redraw.

      @{u}Off@{uu}
	 Disable automatic redraw.

      @{u}Left@{uu}
	 Left edge (in buffer pixels) of area to redraw.

      @{u}Top@{uu}
	 Top Edge (in buffer pixels) of area to redraw.

      @{u}Width@{uu}
	 Width (in buffer pixels) of area to redraw.

      @{u}Height@{uu}
	 Height (in buffer pixels) of area to redraw.

      Note:  If no arguments are given, the entire screen is redrawn.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node RedrawPalette "RedrawPalette"

REDRAWPALETTE (2.1)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      RedrawPalette

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
