WBTOFRONT

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      WBToFront
      WB2Front (1.50)

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Bring the Workbench screen to the front.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      None.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Wedge "Wedge"

WEDGE

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Wedge Object/A,Name/A,Remove/S,Port/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}


      Port Wedges are generally only useful in asynchronous Arexx programs.

      WARNING:	Only use this if you know exactly what you are doing,
	 especially port wedges.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Object@{uu}
	 Wedge object.	The following wedge types are defined:

     S@{u}ELECTDOWN@{uu}
	 You will be notified whenever the left mouse button is pressed
	 down in the preview window.  The message will be in the form
	 "SELECTDOWN x y".

     S@{u}ELECTUP@{uu}
	 You will be notified whenever the left mouse button is released in
	 the preview window.  The message will be in the form "SELECTUP x
	 y".

     M@{u}OUSEMOVE@{uu}
	 You will be notified whenever the mouse is moved with the left
	 button pressed in the preview window.	The message will be in the
	 form "MOUSEMOVE x y".

     T@{u}OOLUP@{uu}
	 You will be notified whenever the user completes any of the
	 drawing tools.  The message will be in the form "TOOLUP
	 toolnumber".

     T@{u}OOLTRAP@{uu}
	 Like TOOLUP, except the drawing operation will not be performed.
	 Same format as TOOLUP.

      @{u}Name@{uu}
	 Name of an Arexx macro to execute when the wedge object occurs;
	 wedge parameters will be passed as command line arguments.

      @{u}Remove@{uu}
	 If specified, the given wedge will be removed from the system. You
	 should always remove your wedges when you are done with them.

      @{u}Port@{uu}
	 If specified, the Name argument is taken to be an Arexx port name,
	 where a message will be sent when the wedge object occurs.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Window "Window"

WINDOW

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Window Name/A

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Open the specified window, identified by name.  The command does not
      return until the window is closed.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Name@{uu}
	 Name of the window to open.  Should be one of the following:

	 Prefs		 Preferences window.
	 About		 About window.
	 Modes		 Drawing modes window.
	 Fill		 Fill options window.
	 Scale		 Scaling window.
	 Airbrush	 Airbrush options window.
	 Balanc 	 Balanc window.
	 Composit	 Composite window.
	 Rotate 	 Rotate window.
	 Buffer 	 Buffer menu window.
	 Brush		 Brush menu window.
	 WaveGen	 Wave generator window.
	 Wave		 Save format window.
	 Pen		 Pen/grid window.
	 Aspect 	 Set Aspect window.
	 Crop		 Crop window.
	 Delete 	 Delete Buffer window.
	 Region (2.0)	 Region window.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node WritePixels "WritePixels"

WRITEPIXELS (AREXX ONLY)

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      WritePixels Var/A,Row/N/A,Width/N,LeftEdge/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Write a block of pixels to a specified scanline of the main buffer.
      This can only be used from Arexx, as it requires a variable from
      which to read the pixel data.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Var@{uu}
	 Specifies the name of the Arexx variable from which to read the
	 pixel information.  The information is stored as a byte-packed
	 string of digits in the order “RGBRGBRGB...”; for example ‘FF0000
	 00FF00 0000FF’x would be three pixels of bright red, green, and
	 blue respectively.  When writing to a greyscale buffer, only one
	 byte per pixel is used; thus ‘FF 80 40’x would be 3 pixels of
	 high, medium, and low intensity grey.	Be careful that Arexx does
	 not expand your bariable name; you must enclose it in quotes
	 within the Arexx program like this:

	 newpixels = REVERSE(myvar)
	    WritePixels 'NEWPIXELS' 0 320 0
	    /* etc.... */


	 You should always specify the variable in upper case, as all
	 variables are converted to upper case by Arexx.

      @{u}Row@{uu}
	 Scanline of the image where the pixel information is stored.
	 Scanlines are numbered starting with 0 at the top and going down
	 to Height-1 at the bottom.  An error will be returned if you try
	 to write outside the bounds of the main buffer.

      @{u}Width@{uu}
	 Number of pixels to write to the specified scanline.  If not
	 specified, the entire width of the scanline is assumed.

      @{u}LeftEdge@{uu}
	 How far from the left edge of the image to start writing.  This
	 value should range from 0 (at the leftmost edge) to the width of
	 the image minus 1.  If not specified, a left offset of 0 is
	 assumed.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Xor "Xor"

XOR

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Xor Alpha/S,Scale/S

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Perform a composite exclusive-or operation between the main and swap
      buffers.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Alpha@{uu}
	 If specified, the alpha channel will be used as a blend to control
	 image during the composite.

      @{u}Scale@{uu}
	 If specified, the swap buffer will be scaled to the size of the
	 region processed.

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
      None.

@endnode

@node Yellow "Yellow"

YELLOW

   @{b}FORMAT@{ub}
      Yellow Adjust/N

   @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
      Adjust the yellow content of the current image or region.

   @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
      @{u}Adjust@{uu}
	 Amount to adjust the yellow (-127 to +127).

   @{b}RESULT@{ub}
